BACKGROUND INFORMATIONAbout me:My name is Tomás Dietz. I’m Australian born; a flamenco dancer/teacher by profession. I have Scottish, German and Motu heritage. I'm 50 years of age, and live in Sydney, Australia.My story points to the Motu people, the tribes which inhabit 13 villages in the narrow tropical savannah region of Central Province, Papua New Guinea.My Motu descent is through my mother, Hane Igua Hila, a Motuan from Hanuabada village. My mum is fiercely proud of her ancient heritage and the cultural traditions that are part of her direct experience. In her youth she watched her grandmother making clay cooking-pots on her lap; she was transitioned from wearing grass skirts every day to wearing cotton dresses; and she bears the traditional body tattoos of her people.Although I’m proudly born and raised Australian, I also deeply treasure my Motu ancestry and am fortunate to have been brought up bi-lingual and bi-cultural.My concerns:Sadly, mum’s culture has been seriously eroded since it was first exposed to foreign influence over 100 years ago. Ever since then the Motu have grown to de-value their ancient cultural practices. But they've lost enough. They need to re-value the knowledge and skills they've refined over thousands of years that are now on the brink of extinction. They need to believe that traditional practices can co-exist with modern lifestyles, or even to evolve with them. If work like mine is left much longer I fear this will very soon lead to irreversible cultural loss as elders who know the details die out. Cultural loss has a profound impact on the social fabric of a people.I cannot sit and watch this culture die off.  I have the commitment and drive to bring about change - all I need is community funds to enable my planned work.This is what inspired my initiative - the project I've called, 'GIDA'.'Gida' is the Motu word for ‘embers’, implying that the cultural traditions that have subsided to embers can either be left to die down to cold coals, or actively fanned back into flame.SPECIFIC FOCUS FOR THIS PROJECT: MOTU POTTERYMany aspects of traditional Motu culture are endangered (eg the language, herbal medicine, children’s games etc), and they are all interlinked somehow, but the most urgent need is to save the endangered pottery tradition from extinction. Mrs Boio Moi is the last surviving potter in Boera (one of the 13 Motu villages). She embodies the final connection to the practice. The need to save her knowledge is critical, not just for Motu people, but for the bank of knowledge and achievement that is the heritage of all humans.WHY IS POTTERY REVIVAL SUCH A BIG DEAL?There are many ways that the revival of Motu pottery can contribute to overall cultural well-being:• To empower women by establishing a Women’s Pottery Society managed by women, the traditional caretakers of the industry, returning to them the status that was once their birthright.• Village workshops will be established through the Pottery Society, for women to teach traditional pottery skills.• Intercultural opportunities exist for non-Motuans to attend such workshops, which can be developed to include broader Motu village experiences, such as family stays or traditional fishing expeditions.• Pots made at the workshops can be marketed for sale and exhibited in galleries as Motu works of art - existing outlets will be enriched, and new outlets can be created.• Youth will be specifically targeted and involved, as I plan to negotiate the introduction of Motu pottery into the school curriculum; their involvement with pottery production at home will also give them a strong sense of inclusion, identity and pride in the village context.• A TV programme of inspired cookery and nutrition will be launched to encourage the use of non-toxic traditional cooking-pots as desirable and preferable to aluminium pots.• Attendant small business will emerge - for instance clay collection, processing and supply.• I envisage the revival of traditional trade partnerships, for example with the Kerema people of the Gulf who traditionally traded sago and other goods in exchange for Motu pottery - this was the former Hiri trade event carried out via lagatoi boats, but today this could be interpreted by motor boat or land vehicles, opening up entrepreneurial avenues for transportation/cargo businesses.• I also see the creation of an annual Motu Pottery Festival in villages featuring thatch stalls where potters exhibit and sell their wares to tourists amid traditional feasting and celebration. The reliable influx of visitors will provide opportunities for villagers to sell a diverse range of items, eg craft goods and Motu food. These are just some ideas which also encourage the preservation of other traditional practices such as singing and dancing, traditional jewellery and adornment.The scope is enormous, and the potential for social repair and empowerment is immeasurable.WHAT WE NEED:Budget: AUD$31,370 This will enable me to take a small team of four people (2 researchers + 2 technicians) from Sydney to Boera for a month to document the details of Motu pottery construction, and to record the oral history of Mrs Boio Moi. I will produce a two video documentaries: one, a short general interest video, and the other a detailed technical video for training purposes for use in Gida's implementation programmes. I will also prepare a written report for submission to PNG research authorities and UNESCO.Fixed Expenses:
Airfares and transfers (airfares are economy return Sydney/Port Moresby);
Visas;
Budget accommodation in Port Moresby and in Boera;
Materials & equipment (video/stills camera, voice recorder)
Hire of vehicle for local fieldwork.
Variable Expenses:
Essential living expenses (food/incidentals);
Remuneration for Mrs Moi;
Goodwill gifts for local helpers;
Petrol (gasoline) for Fieldwork vehicle;
Data storage cards;
Stationery supplies;
Telephone costs.
The Research Team will comprise:   1.  Project Manager   2.  Field Assistant   3.  Videographer   4.  PhotographerWHAT DO YOU GET FROM DONATING?There are several perk options for specific donation amounts, but more importantly, you are participating in the salvation of ancient knowledge.You are contributing directly to the well-being of a vulnerable people. They may never meet you, but you have their deepest gratitude, along with mine.WHAT WILL THE TEAM ACTUALLY DO IN BOERA?Our objectives are:
To record every aspect of Motu pottery production as known to Mrs Boio Moi, by means of photography and video documentary filming;
To interview Mrs Moi and record her oral history;
To identify ways to revive the relevance of pottery to Motu people;
To identify outlets for Motu pottery beyond the village environment to offer village potters potential sources of additional income and give further incentive for them to maintain production;
To investigate the possibility to revive traditional trading partnerships, eg with the Kerema people (traditionally the Motu people traded their pots for sago and other produce from the Kerema people in the more fertile Gulf area). This would rekindle inter-village bonds, improve their diet and health, and gain more control of their own destiny and well-being, and allow other villages to once again enjoy the benefits of cooking with traditional pots;
Project Team Members who will facilitate the delivery of future village workshops will learn how to make Motu pots, so that they’re better able to motivate others to learn and ensure the longevity of the revival;
To collate the findings from this research into formats that the general public can access easily and freely, eg videos that can be kept in libraries.
To enter traditional pottery skills into the school curriculum at primary, secondary and tertiary levels.
GENERAL INTEREST VIDEO:The film material will be used to create to a human interest programme for the broader community via television. Already SBS TV Australia journalists have expressed the desire to be involved. This represents a significant support to our work in terms of public awareness.TECHNICAL VIDEO: Specific skills & techniques to be filmed for teaching programmes:
Identifying and collecting natural clay at source;
Identifying and collecting the correct sand for temper;
Sorting of the clay;
Collecting seawater;
Adding seawater to the clay;  
Kneading;
Clay pug formation;
Initial wall construction by hand;
Wall construction by anvil/paddle technique;
Lip construction;
Surface finishing;
Drying;
Baking (firing) - fire construction and addition of greenware pots, temperature control;
Handling tongs construction and usage;
Tool making and usage, eg anvil and paddle, tools of decoration;
Decoration traditions, eg etching of tattoo designs, shell indentations.
Where do the funds go if we don't reach our entire goal? If funds don't initially reach the entire goal, the Research Team will either be reduced accordingly, and/or the expenses will be further pared down, or the funds will be held while fundraising continues until sufficient funds have been raised to send the team to Boera Village.Where do the funds go if there is surplus?Surplus funds will be directed into the Boera project as needed in the field work and later for the implenentation programmes, and also invested for use in future Gida projects. Gida's work is enormous, and does not end with the Boera Pottery project.What happens to the equipment that is bought for this project?Equipment is an investment for use in all future Gida Fieldwork.The Impact of your involvement:This project has enormous and long lasting benefit for the social fabric of the Motu people. Your contributions will directly help to rescue ancient human traditions and enrich the lives and culture of thousands of people.  The knowledge you're helping to save is significant not just for Motu people, but for the bank of knowledge and achievement that is the heritage of all humans on this planet.RISKS & CHALLENGES TO THE PROJECT:The main hurdle is finding funds. This project is privately driven and non-profit.  I do not yet have sponsorship from large corporations and organisations. Without funding this project cannot move forward.Solution to the funding problem? The global community - you can help directly. Indiegogo Crowd Funding can quickly involve people from all over the planet, such as yourself, to mobilise this important project.Another challenge in this area is emotional commitment to detail. Academics tend to record such cultural expressions in general terms and concepts for books and articles. What's the answer to commitment? Me! I'm personally and deeply committed as a passionate Motuan. I have insight into the culture and speak the language, so I'll attend to recording every detail and nuance because it's meaningful to me and all Motuans - it's the only way for living cultural knowledge to be passed on to the next generation.Other Ways You Can Help:If you can’t contribute with funds, you can still help by spreading the word - your friends and workmates may be willing to help. They too can help spread the word, and maybe this way my quest will find its way to UNESCO or other humanitarian organisations who can support my quest. Please, use the Indiegogo share tools at the top of the page. Thank you for your support - Tomás.======================================================FURTHER SOURCES OF INFORMATION ABOUT THE WORK OF GIDA:Official Gida Website + Newsletter subscription (also our Contact Form in case you have any queries not covered here)<http://www.tomasflamenco.wix.com/gida>Gida Facebook Group:<https://www.facebook.com/groups/Gidagida/>
